  abstract = {Massive exoplanets are observed preferentially around high metallicity ({[}Fe/H{]}) stars while low-mass exoplanets do not show such an effect. This so-called planet-metallicity correlation generally favors the idea that most observed gas giants at \$r\ensuremath{<}10\$ AU are formed via a core accretion process. We investigate the origin of this phenomenon using a semi-analystical model, wherein the standard core accretion takes place at planet traps in protostellar disks where rapid type I migrators are halted. We focus on the three major exoplanetary populations - hot-Jupiters, exo-Jupiters located at \$r {\textbackslash}simeq 1\$ AU, and the low-mass planets. We show using a statistical approach that the planet-metallicity correlations are well reproduced in these models. We find that there are specific transition metallicities with values {[}Fe/H{]}\$=-0.2\$ to \$-0.4\$, below which the low-mass population dominates, and above which the Jovian populations take over. The exo-Jupiters significantly exceed the hot-Jupiter population at all observed metallicities. The low-mass planets formed via the core accretion are insensitive to metallicity, which may account for a large fraction of the observed super-Earths and hot-Neptunes. Finally, a controlling factor in building massive planets is the critical mass of planetary cores (\$M\_\{c,crit\}\$) that regulates the onset of runaway gas accretion. Assuming the current data is roughly complete at {[}Fe/H{]}\$\ensuremath{>}-0.6\$, our models predict that the most likely value of the "mean" critical core mass of Jovian planets is \${\textbackslash}braket\{\vphantom{\}}M\_\{c,crit\}\vphantom{\{}\} {\textbackslash}simeq 5 M\_\{{\textbackslash}oplus\}\$ rather than \$10 M\_\{{\textbackslash}oplus\}\$. This implies that grain opacities in accreting envelopes should play an important role in lowering \$M\_\{c,crit\}\$.},
